{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0805d3e-9cda-4abe-8a8d-9f49aa913435","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting and bloating the trace.\n- `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` (the default) must not be disabled, or the diagnostic port won't be available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b5facd9-69ee-4da5-9745-ceb431cf2b45","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"D811:283A56:33BDF8F:3894408:69FBEAF5"},"id":"4ba883b1-ec0f-4a89-abf1-b74c7b5413a0","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:29:34.388Z","parentId":"f460ac74-95c2-4b29-8bb2-3665398cd11b"}
